1) Scope & Requirements (research checklist)
	HTTP Core

	(M) HTTP/1.1 parsing (request line, headers), persistent connections (Connection: keep-alive/close), timeouts.

	(M) Methods: GET, POST, DELETE.

	(M) Status codes & default/error pages.

	(M) Static file serving; directory listing (autoindex) toggle.

	(M) CGI: run external programs via fork()+execve(), pass env, connect stdin/stdout.

	(M) Multiple virtual servers (IP:port + server_name) and locations with per-location rules.

	(M) Redirections (3xx), index files, root/alias, method allowance/denial.

	(M) Upload handling (commonly required through POST + multipart/form-data to a configured upload dir).

	(M) No threads for connection handling; use select/poll/epoll/kqueue (typically poll() accepted everywhere).

Common Bonus

	(B) Platform-specific poller (epoll/ kqueue) with edge-triggering.

	(B) Chunked transfer-encoding (request and/or response).

	(B) HTTP/1.1 connection reuse optimizations; pipelining (if allowed).

	(B) Advanced CGI mapping (per extension), interpreter shebang handling.

	(B) Range requests / partial content.

	(B) Improved logging/metrics; graceful reload; hot config reload (often non-mandatory).

	(B) TLS termination (usually out of scope unless allowed).

2) Architecture (high-level, OOP)
	Layers

		Core/Infra: Event loop, sockets, timers, file I/O, subprocess (CGI), logging.

		HTTP: Stream parser (incremental), request/response model, routing, body handling, encoder/decoder.

		Server runtime: Virtual server selection, location matching, method dispatchers, handlers (static, upload, delete, cgi).

		Config: Grammar, AST, validation -> runtime model (data-driven behavior).

		Observability: Access logs, error logs, metrics (req/sec, latency), debug tracing.

		CLI & bootstrap: Config load, daemonization (if allowed), signal handling, shutdown.

	Key Classes (suggested)

		EventLoop (reactor): owns Poller (select/poll/epoll), TimerWheel, callback registry.

		Listener (per bind): accepts sockets, hands off to ConnectionManager.

		Connection (stateful): read/write buffers, state machine (REQ_HEADERS → REQ_BODY → ROUTE → RESP_HEADERS → RESP_BODY).

		HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HeaderMap, BodyReader/Writer.

		Router, RouteMatcher, VirtualServer, Location.

		StaticFileHandler, UploadHandler, DeleteHandler, CgiHandler.

		CgiProcess (child process wrapper): env builder, pipes, timeouts, kill/cleanup.

		ConfigParser (lexer+parser), ConfigModel (POCOs: ServerBlock, LocationBlock, Directive).

		MimeTypes, ErrorPages, Logger, AccessLogFormatter.

		Limits (max body size, timeouts), Security (path sanitization, method allowlist).

		Design note: Keep Connection minimal—no business logic. It advances a finite state machine and delegates to handlers.

3) Data-Driven Configuration
	Goals
		No hardcoded behavior. 
		Everything driven by config: roots, indexes, upload dir, cgi mapping, allowed methods, error pages, autoindex, max body size, redirects.

		Config Model (typical)


				server {
				listen 127.0.0.1:8080;
				server_name example.local;

				error_page 404 /errors/404.html;
				client_max_body_size 10m;

				location / {
					root /var/www/html;
					index index.html index.htm;
					autoindex off;
				}

				location /upload {
					methods POST;
					upload_store /var/www/uploads;
				}

				location /cgi-bin {
					cgi_pass /usr/bin/python3;   # or map by extension
					cgi_extension .py .cgi;
					timeout 5s;
				}

				location /old {
					return 301 /new;
				}
				}

		Validation pass

		Duplicate ports/server_name conflicts, invalid paths, missing files, bad perms.

		Directive compatibility (e.g., upload_store requires POST).

		Limits sanity (client_max_body_size, timeouts).

		Normalize paths; prevent directory traversal.

		Parsing approach

		You already have AST experience—use a recursive descent parser with a small EBNF and produce a typed ConfigModel. Add source locations for helpful error messages.


4) Eventing & Concurrency Model

		Single-threaded event loop (M). poll() is portable; epoll/kqueue for (B).

		Non-blocking sockets, back-pressure via output buffer watermarks.

		Timers: per-connection idle/read/write timeouts; per-CGI exec timeout; keep-alive timeout.

		Zero-copy where possible (sendfile optional) with cautious portability.


5) HTTP Pipeline (state machines)
		Request parsing (incremental)

		Start-line → headers (CRLF strictness) → body strategy:

		Content-Length

		(B) Transfer-Encoding: chunked

		Enforce client_max_body_size.

		Normalize headers (case-insensitive keys); preserve original case for forwarding only if needed.

		Routing

		Select VirtualServer by Host + socket.

		Longest-prefix Location match; then method allowlist; then handler selection.

		Response

		Build headers late (when you know Content-Length), else (B) stream chunked.

		Correct status codes, Date header, Connection policy.

		MIME type by extension.

6) Handlers
		StaticFileHandler (M)

		Map path → filesystem; guard against traversal (..), symlink policy (decide).

		index fallback; else autoindex (if enabled).

		ETag (simple mtime+size) (B), Last-Modified (B).

		UploadHandler (M)

		multipart/form-data parsing, store files under upload_store.

		Enforce size/filename sanitation; collision policy.

		DeleteHandler (M)

		Remove file under root; ensure no escape from root.

		CgiHandler (M)

		Build CGI env (REQUEST_METHOD, SCRIPT_NAME, QUERY_STRING, CONTENT_TYPE, CONTENT_LENGTH, SERVER_NAME, SERVER_PORT, GATEWAY_INTERFACE=CGI/1.1, etc.).

		fork() child, dup2 pipes to stdin/stdout, execve() program or interpreter + script.

		Read CGI headers + body; map to HTTP response.

		Timeouts & kill on overrun; limit memory with setrlimit if allowed.

7) Reliability, Limits, Security
		Timeouts: handshake/read/write/keep-alive/CGI.

		Resource caps: max open fds, per-conn buffers, uploads, CGI runtime/mem.

		Path sanitation & root jail (no .. resolution outside root).

		Graceful shutdown: stop accepting, drain in-flight, wait CGI with deadline, then close.

		Error handling: centralized error mapper; friendly messages; custom error pages.

		Logging: access log (common/combined), error log with levels, request ID for tracing.

8) Testing Strategy (TDD-first)
		Test Harness & Tools

		Unit tests: GoogleTest or Catch2.

		Integration: Python/C++ test client or curl; scripted golden files.

		E2E: ab/wrk for load; custom scripts for timeouts/errors.

		Fuzz: header/body fuzzing with libFuzzer (bonus but valuable).

		Sanitizers: ASan, UBSan; Valgrind for leaks.

		Unit tests (examples)

		Config lexer/parser → AST → Model (valid/invalid cases).

		Router (virtual server, location precedence).

		HTTP parser: lines, headers, folding (if supported), body with CL, oversized body, malformed input.

		Multipart parser: boundaries, nested parts, filename quirks.

		Autoindex rendering with special filenames.

		CGI env builder; header parse from CGI output (bad/missing headers → 502).

		Integration scenarios

		Static: 200, 404, 403, 301/302 redirects.

		Keep-alive reuse; idle timeout closure.

		Uploads: small/large, type variations, rejected oversize.

		DELETE success/failure (permissions, not found).

		CGI: GET/POST, long stdout, bad exit code, timeouts, stderr logging.

		Edge cases: slowloris (partial headers), client abort mid-body, zero-length body.

		Data-driven tests

		Fixture folders per scenario: config/, input/, expected/.

		Tests read fixtures → spin server → run scripted client → compare expected/ byte-for-byte.

